on至少有5個女兒。"},"zh-hans":{"–":"殁","–Female":"殁","1428–Female":"1428年–殁","1607–Female":"1607年–殁","–Male":"殁","abt 1607":"大约1607年","1607":"1607年","1428":"1428年","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"英国英格兰藍卡爾維根","Barton, Lancashire, England":"英国藍卡爾巴頓","lifeSummary":"Andrew Booth和Litton至少有5个女儿。"},"hr":{"–":"preminuo","–Female":"preminula","1428–Female":"1428.–preminula","1607–Female":"1607–preminula","–Male":"preminuo","abt 1607":"oko 1607.","1607":"1607","1428":"1428.","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"cs":{"–":"Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1428–Female":"1428–Zesnulá","1607–Female":"1607–Zesnulá","–Male":"Zesnulý","abt 1607":"okolo 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"–":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1428–Female":"1428–Afdød","1607–Female":"1607–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","abt 1607":"omkring 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1428–Female":"1428–Overleden","1607–Female":"1607–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","abt 1607":"circa 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1428–Female":"1428–Deceased","1607–Female":"1607–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","abt 1607":"about 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Booth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>bothe</i> (Old Danish <i>bōth</i>) ‘temporary shelter, such as a covered market stall or a cattle-herdsman's hut’. The latter sense was predominant in the Pennines of Lancashire and Yorkshire, where there were many cattle farms or vaccaries, and whose subdivisions were known as ‘booths’. The principal meaning of the surname there was therefore probably ‘cattle herdsman’, ‘man in charge of a vaccary’, and thus identical with   Boothman  . Elsewhere it may have denoted a shopkeeper who owned a temporary market stall, but no evidence has been found to confirm this use of the surname. In the British Isles the surname is still more common in northern England, where Scandinavian influence was more marked, and in Scotland, where the word was borrowed into Gaelic as <i>both(an)</i>.","History: Robert Booth (1604–72) is mentioned in the colonial records of Exeter, NH, in 1645. He subsequently moved to ME."],"variants":[{"name":"Boothman","meanings":["English (northern): occupational name from Middle English <i>both</i> (Old Danish <i>bōth</i>) ‘temporary shelter, such as a covered market stall or a cattle-herdsman's hut’ + <i>man</i>. In the Pennine uplands of northern England, where booths were subdivisons of vaccaries or cattle-rearing establishment, the name probably denoted a herdsman who looked after cattle, perhaps a man in charge of a vaccary. Elsewhere the surname might have denoted a shopkeeper but evidence for this lacking. Alternatively, the name can also be an occupational name for a servant of a man surnamed   Booth  ."]},{"name":"Boothe","meanings":["English: variant of   Booth  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Andrew Booth had at least 5 daughters with Litton."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1607–Female":"1607–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","abt 1607":"umbes 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1428–Female":"1428–Kuollut","1607–Female":"1607–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","abt 1607":"noin 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1428–Female":"1428–Décédée","1607–Female":"1607–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","abt 1607":"environ 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Andrew Booth a eu au moins 5 filles avec Litton."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1428–Female":"1428–Verstorben","1607–Female":"1607–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","abt 1607":"um 1607","1607":"1607","1428":"1428","of Wigan, Lancs., Eng.":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Andrew Booth hatte mit Litton mindestens 5 Töchter."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","–Female":"Desede","1428–Female":"1428–Desede","1607–Female":"